                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 312.11/285.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">American Consul at Chihuahua</gloss>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.—Paraphrase.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-04-27T18:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">April 27, 1912—6 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Your April 24, 5 p.m. Bearing in mind Department’s March 27, 4, p.m., regarding
                    payment of taxes, you will informally protest to appropriate persons exercising
                    de facto authority in your district <pb facs="1026" n="910" xml:id="pg_910"/>
                    against all arbitrary, illegal or confiscatory exactions made by such persons
                    upon American citizens or their property. In matter of “forced loans” you will
                    distinguish between levy in the form of war taxes equally applied according to a
                    fixed percentage amongst all the inhabitants of the country, whether natives or
                    foreigners, and exactions levied arbitrarily upon a part only of the community.
                    See volume 6, Moore’s Digest, page 915.</p>
                <p>Referring again to Department’s March 27, 4 p.m., protests should be entered
                    against payment of all taxes to insurrectionary authorities; you will also enter
                    special and emphatic protests informally and unofficially against arbitrary and
                    discriminatory exactions, “forced loans.” Protests should be recorded if
                    possible.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Knox.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
